description: From Middle English artificial (“man-made”) via Old French (modern French artificiel), from Latin artificiālis from artificium (“skill”), from artifex, from ars (“skill”), and -fex, from facere (“to make”). Displaced native Old English cræftlīċ.

adjectives.description: artificial (comparative more artificial, superlative most artificial)

entries.meaning: Man-made; made by humans; of artifice.
examples: The flowers were artificial, and he thought them rather tacky.

entries.meaning: Not natural or normal: imposed arbitrarily or without regard to the specifics or normal circumstances of a person, a situation, etc.
(bridge) Conveying some meaning other than the actual contents of one's hand.
